'''Skinner Releasing Technique''' is a movement training method in which certified teachers employ [[wiktionary:imagery|imagery]], [[voice]] and [[music]] as stimuli for unstructured, [[improvisation|improvised]] movements in their students.<ref name=allison>{{citation|title=The illustrated encyclopedia of body-mind disciplines|author=Nancy Allison|page=265}}</ref> The trademark for this method is held by Skinner Releasing Institute.<ref>{{citation | title=United States Patent and Trademark Office, Serial Number 73253765, March 13, 1980}}</ref> Although Skinner Releasing Technique is sometimes compared to dance techniques, it differs significantly from conventional dance techniques such as [[turnout (ballet)|turnout]] and [[spotting (dance technique)|spotting]], in which body form and movement are rigorously specified. Instead this method is [[somatics|somatic]] in nature, emphasizing the internal sensory experience of the practitioner.<ref name= "Knaster">{{cite book |last= Knaster |first= Mirka |year= 1996 |title= Discovering the Body's Wisdom: A Comprehensive Guide to More Than Fifty Mind-Body Practices |publisher= [[Bantam Books|Bantam]] |pages= 268–70 |isbn= 9780307575500}}</ref> Skinner Releasing Technique was invented by Joan Skinner, a [[Professor Emeritus]] at [[University of Washington]].<ref>{{Cite web| author = University of Washington web | title = ''University of Washington Dance Faculty'' | url = http://depts.washington.edu/uwdance/faculty.html | accessdate = 2008-03-18 }}</ref>
